I believe this is a way to scrape A03 stories without using an account. Once you arrived at the story url, AO3 prompts you with a TOS agreement where you have to check a box and hit agree. If you allow cookies you only have to do this once when browsing normally, but in the html for the "tos agreement" page is a href to #main. Basically the story, but the default way for AO3 to show stories for some reason is by chapter. So if you enter url2 while on the "TOS agreement page" it will take you to the chapter view and after 1.5 seconds or so, it will take you back to the "TOS agreement page". Trying to go to the "full work" url whilst on the "TOS agreement" page will only take you to the chapter view of the story. It turns out if you happen to press the "see FULL work" button within the 1.5 seconds of time before the "TOS agreement page" pops up it will take you to the actual full work, but after 1.5 seconds it will take you back to the "TOS agreement page". Mere seconds seems to be all the time we need and you just open a session and get the urls below in succession to replicate what I just illustrated.


#!/usr/bin/env python3

# URLS
url1 = 'https://archiveofourown.org/works/xxxxxxxx'
url2 = 'https://archiveofourown.org/works/xxxxxxxx#main'
url3 = 'https://archiveofourown.org/works/xxxxxxxx?view_full_work=true'

# Start the session
import requests
session = requests.Session()
r1 = session.get(url1)
r2 = session.get(url2)
r3 = session.get(url3)

# "parse" html
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(r3.content, 'html.parser')
print(soup.prettify())

Sorry if I ramble or don't make sense, really tired about to go to bed.

Basically the following
>species
>smut level
>length
>setting/Franchise
>description/synopsis

I made the mistake of trying to tag like fanfiction sites and sofurry when I first started off. I created obnoxiously long taglines that named every sexual and sensual act no matter how nuanced it was. There are some still in the catalog like that.

When it comes to tags I learned that there are two types. Ones for helping people find your story (e.g. snekdog, BHA, slow burn, post-apoc); these are more common tags that everybody knows and most your tags will probably be this. And ones that describe your story once the reader find them (e.g., shedding, alcohol, Ohio, crash landing, indiscriminate fuck spree, /k/ fic); these are more experimental, unique, or "not the main focus". They basically try to do what the description/synopsis does, which is why if you are stuck trying to find the right tag, don't sweat, just put the generic tags in, and put the rest of the descriptors in your description/synopsis.

In all there is a general gist of tagging as I pointed out, but when it comes down to it, an art in of itself with no one way of doing it.

Having gone through the same issue myself, the only advice I can give you is, quite literally, just do it. Just write. Don't even think, just write. You can go back later and fix and tweak whatever, but you'll never get anywhere if you just sit and wallow.
You need to get out of your headspace. Drink a little, put on some favorite music, get the thermometer to just the right temp, get those super comfy pajamas you love so much, whatever you gotta do to feel good, do it. But also, write while you do it.
Writer's block isn't even really about not having ideas or being unable to write. You know you can write. Fuck, you wrote the post to tell us this, after all.
I know the feelings you're likely going through with this block. I know it can be a struggle. But the worst thing you can do it give in to those feelings, cuz then you'll just end up being trapped inside your mind, unable to get anything accomplished.
If you need to talk further on this, or just in general, you got people here willing to help. I know I am, at least.
>https://bed-man.sofurry.com/
